{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476947"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13997"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13997"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.35,0.02,0.02,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1272"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6054"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48777"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent after falling from a playground slide onto his outstretched left arm. He complains of severe pain and swelling around his left elbow. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His left elbow is grossly swollen and deformed. He is unable to move his elbow and resists any attempt at passive movement due to pain. Distal pulses are present but weak, and capillary refill time is four seconds. There is decreased sensation in the radial nerve distribution of the hand. An X-ray of the elbow is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gartland type II supracondylar fracture","Gartland type IV supracondylar fracture","Gartland type I supracondylar fracture","Flexion-type supracondylar fracture","Gartland type III supracondylar fracture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and X-ray findings are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003EGartland type III supracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. This type of fracture is characterised by complete displacement of the distal fragment with no cortical contact. The mechanism of injury (fall onto an outstretched hand), age group (typically 5-7 years old), and the presence of significant swelling and deformity all support this diagnosis. The neurovascular compromise (weak pulses, prolonged capillary refill time, and decreased sensation) is a serious complication often associated with Gartland type III fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGartland type I supracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is non-displaced or minimally displaced, and this would not describe the severe deformity and neurovascular compromise seen in this case. These fractures are typically managed conservatively with immobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGartland type II supracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E involves displacement of the distal fragment but with intact posterior cortex. While this can cause significant pain and swelling, it typically does not result in the degree of deformity and neurovascular compromise described in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGartland type IV supracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is a more severe variant where the fracture is multidirectionally unstable due to periosteal disruption circumferentially. While this type can certainly cause significant deformity and neurovascular compromise, it is less common than type III and typically requires open reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexion-type supracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon variant (about 2-3% of supracondylar fractures) where the distal fragment is displaced anteriorly. This type of fracture usually results from a fall onto a flexed elbow, which is not the mechanism described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of a Gartland type III supracondylar fracture involves urgent closed reduction and percutaneous pinning under general anaesthesia. The neurovascular status must be closely monitored, and compartment syndrome should be considered if there is no improvement post-reduction. These fractures require careful follow-up to ensure proper healing and to monitor for complications such as cubitus varus deformity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supracondylar fractures are common elbow injuries in children, typically resulting from falls onto an outstretched hand.","Gartland type III supracondylar fractures are completely displaced with no cortical contact.","Neurovascular compromise is a serious complication of supracondylar fractures and requires urgent assessment and management."],"references":["Supracondylar fracture of the humerus \u2013 emergency department. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/fractures/supracondylar_fracture_of_the_humerus_emergency_department/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13997"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20893"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20893"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XxvfdWSMDYVX19Ja1dIcU2h77yXtEL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XxvfdWSMDYVX19Ja1dIcU2h77yXtEL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":656,"height":750}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35181"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T17:15:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T16:08:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nul